author: @jyothinkjayan6508
text: import numpy as np grid=[         [0,7,0,0,0,1,9,0,0],         [0,0,0,0,6,0,0,5,0],         [0,0,9,0,0,0,0,0,3],         [0,0,5,6,0,0,0,0,0],         [0,2,8,0,3,0,0,0,0],         [7,0,3,0,0,5,0,0,0],         [1,0,7,9,0,0,0,0,2],         [2,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,6],         [3,0,0,1,0,0,0,0,0]      ]  def possible(y,x,n):     global grid     for i in range(0,9):#i=0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8         if grid[y][i]==n:             return False     for i in range(0,9):         if grid[i][x]==n:             return False     x0=(x//3)*3         y0=(y//3)*3        for i in range(0,3):             for j in range(0,3):                 if grid[y0+i][x0+j]==n:                     return False     return True  def solve():     global grid     for y in range(9):                    for x in range(9):                  if grid[y][x]==0:                     for n in range(1,10):                         if possible(y,x,n):                             grid[y][x]=n                             #print(np.matrix(grid))                              solve()                             grid[y][x]=0                     return     print(np.matrix(grid)) solve()  Hi sir this is the program to solve the 9X9 sudoku using backtracking. This gives proper output when run as such. I tried to get the grid to be printed each time it gets updated, that's what i have commented inside the if possible condn. when i tried to print that, the grid which last printed was wrong (which was supposed to be the actual fully solved sudoku)[actually the 0X0 cell is 6 in the  fully solved output, but when i print using inner print statement it reaches somewhere around 8 which is not supposed to be as by the program]  , can you tell why it happens so.
